2","display_label":"Sarah Batt married Micajah Torrey Jr. — whose father Micajah.","link_text":"Micajah Torrey"}],"tags":[],"open_questions":["Torrey line not fully researched beyond Weymouth — further descendants possible. See open_research_threads."],"sources":[],"gender":"female","number_of_marriages":2,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"bio":{"display_name":"Sarah Batt White","first_name":"Sarah","last_name":"Torrey","married_names":["Torrey","White"],"maiden_name":"Batt","bio_blurb":"Twice-widowed Weymouth mother of nine"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Married her step-uncle's son","body":"Sarah Batt's stepfather Josiah Torrey was the brother of her husband Micajah Torrey Jr.'s father Micajah Torrey Sr. — Sarah therefore married her step-uncle's son. Her own children were both step-cousins to and children-in-law of the broader Torrey family network. The step-family marriage pattern was common in colonial New England where remarriages frequently rearranged the kinship of small village populations."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Nine documented children with Micajah Torrey Jr.","body":"Sarah and Micajah Torrey Jr. had nine documented children. The marriage produced the largest single Batt-Torrey family cluster of the late-seventeenth and early-eighteenth-century Boston-and-Weymouth Massachusetts area, with the family settling primarily at Weymouth where Sarah lived out her long widowhood-and-old-age decades."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Lived to ninety; gravestone reads eighty-fifth year","body":"Sarah lived to approximately age ninety — born January 18, 1673 in Boston and died May 10, 1763 in Weymouth, a span of ninety years and three months. The Weymouth gravestone reads 'in ye 85th year of her age' — a discrepancy suggesting either an inaccurate stone inscription or a contemporary error in computing her age. The colonial gravestone tradition of counting the running year rather than completed years often produced such variations."},{"number":4,"category":"family","header":"Boston 1673 to Weymouth Massachusetts 1763","body":"Sarah Batt was born January 18, 1673 in Boston Massachusetts, daughter of Paul Batt and Sarah Wilson Torrey. She died May 10, 1763 in Weymouth Massachusetts. Her ninety-year life spanned from the early years of King Philip's War through to the eve of the American Revolution."},{"number":5,"category":"family","header":"Widowed twice, she married a deacon","body":"Three years after Micajah Torrey died, Sarah married Deacon Samuel White of Braintree, becoming the second wife of a man who outlived her first husband by decades."}],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM659"},"slug":"sarah-torrey-1673"},"X00072":{"id":"X00072","classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1643,"month":10,"day":12,"city":"Weymouth","state":"Massachusetts","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1710,"month":1,"day":20,"country":"United States"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X00073","children_ids":["I00062"],"marriage_number":1,"location_country":"United States"}],"sources":[],"gender":"male","parents":{"father_id":"X00068","mother_id":"X00069"},"tags":[],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Micajah Torrey","first_name":"Micajah","last_name":"Torrey","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"micajah-torrey-1643"},"X00073":{"id":"X00073","classific